highlights.highlight: The esports SKLZ stock saw a spike of investor confidence after the founder’s purchase signaled that the stock may have bottomed out Esports stock Skillz Inc (NYSE:SKLZ) has been making headlines this Easter weekend; recently its CEO and founder, Andrew Paradise, disclosed that he had made a significant share purchase in the trading window post fourth-quarter

Skillz is a San Francisco-based competitive multiplayer mobile video game platform that allows users to compete in a number of global competitions against other players. The transactions were initially spotted on Fintel’s latest CEO purchases page, late on Thursday evening.
Despite the rally, Skillz shares are trading well below the initial SPAC merger price of $10 last seen in mid-2020 and significantly below its all-time high of $46 hit in February of 2021.
Investors were pleased to see the Skillz CEO purchasing the company's shares with his own capital, as it demonstrated his commitment to the business and belief in its growth potential.

For the Final quarter of 2022, Skillz reported a 57% decline in revenue to $46.9 million, slightly missing market consensus expectations. Adjusted EBITDA losses narrowed significantly from $79.5 million in the final quarter of 2021 to a loss of $9.5 million in 2022 as total costs and expenses were reduced significantly.
The post Skillz Soars 24% After CEO and Founder Andrew Paradise Discloses Significant Purchase appeared first on Fintel.

highlights.highlight: First Horizon (NYSE:FHN) quickly rose 3.3% as the CEO of TD Bank (NYSE:TD) was said to be speaking at luncheon sponsored by Bank of America. TD (TD) CEO Bharat Masrani is said to be reiterating his view he still likes First Horizon post the recent Silicon Valley Bank crisis, according to traders, who are hearing the comments second hand.

The CEO comments come after First Horizon (FHN) shares plunged 20% on March 13 amid a bank selloff sparked by the collapse of Silicon Valley Bank and the shares seesawed in weeks after amid regional banking crisis.

TD initiated discussions with First Horizon regarding a potential further extension of the outside date. Wells Fargo upgraded First Horizon (FHN) late last month to overweight and said it still expects TD Bank (TD) to eventually complete its proposed acquisition of FHN at the original agreed-upon price of $25 per share.
